Certainly! Below is a simple example of how you might implement a Flask API endpoint for recommendations. In this scenario, we're using a basic dataset to illustrate the concept without involving complex machine learning models. For a real-world implementation, you can expand this by integrating with an actual database and refining your recommendation logic further.

Example code:

--------------------------------------------------
from flask import Flask, jsonify, request

app = Flask(__name__)

# Sample data representing products with their categories
products = [
    {"id": 1, "name": "Handmade Desk Lamp", "category": "modern"},
    {"id": 2, "name": "Vintage Desk Organizer", "category": "vintage"},
    {"id": 3, "name": "Minimalist Desk Mat", "category": "minimalist"}
]

# Simulated user preferences (in practice, pull from your database or user session)
user_preferences = {
    "user_1": {"preferred_category": "modern"},
    "user_2": {"preferred_category": "vintage"}
}

@app.route('/recommend/<user_id>')

def recommend(user_id):
    # Get user preference, if available
    pref = user_preferences.get(user_id, {})
    preferred_category = pref.get("preferred_category")

    # Filter products based on the user's preferred category
    if preferred_category:
        recommendations = [p for p in products if p["category"] == preferred_category]
    else:
        recommendations = products  # Fallback: return all products if no preference exists

    return jsonify(recommendations)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)
--------------------------------------------------

This code sets up a basic Flask application with a single endpoint '/recommend/<user_id>'. When you access this endpoint with a user ID, it checks for that user's preference and filters the products accordingly. Feel free to extend the logic further by incorporating more nuanced filtering or by connecting it to a dynamic data source.
